title: For Sale:  Range scrap for melting
postcontent: So I got a chance to dig the lead out of an old shooting range berm a while back and melted what I could.  What you see below is 44 lbs of mostly FMJ's that floated to the top because the lead could not escape since the jackets were whole.  So I fired up NetFlix on a laptop and went into my reloading room with a pair of snips and clipped an opening in every bullet.  Now they just need to be melted and the copper jackets will float to the top and scraped off (sell it to a recycler...copper brings good money), leaving you with the best lead alloy for casting into bullets.  I also tossed my pulled bullets and some sprews in the box too, all from the same range scrap.  I also have 15 lbs of uncut FMJ's so you can crack those open yourself.I'd like to sell it all for $1.25 a pound, or all 59 lbs for $65Meet at Bass Pro in St. Charles or ship at your cost.

title: For Sale:  No 4 Mk 1 ROFM Sportersized Barrel Intact ***EXTRAS***
postcontent:
This is a No 4 Mk 1 1941 dated ROFM (Royal Ordinance Factory Maltby) Enfield two groove rifle, it is fully functional and in perfect working order, just not in original condition.
It is a very easy project to finish, and would be quite fun to put back together. I just never ended up sitting down and ordering the parts, so my money started going into other projects. The barrel is fully intact, even the finish is near spotless on the barrel, the action has normal handling wear but still very nice. The bore is sharp and shiny, honestly it looks like it has hardly been shot. Somewhere along the line probably in the 50's after the war someone picked this thing up as surplus and took everything off that made it heavy and it didn't need to shoot, then they sawed the stock off right where the rear band sat, and sawed it a little crooked at that.Now as it sits the barrel free floats, and this old two groove is a tack driver. I had half a mind to just keep it and clean up where the stock was cut a little and call it good, but I know I'd hardly ever pick up enough ammo to shoot it as much as I'd want to, and I don't want to pick up all the stuff to start reloading for it.
It came to me without a magazine and that's another thing I never ended up getting for it.However it does come with the following: - No 4 Mk 2 Bayonet and scabbard- 20 Rounds Original .303 Brit GB49 7 headstamped Mk7 Cordite Ball ammo- 40 Rounds PPU .303 Brit 150 Grn SP BT ammo- 20 Rounds Federal .303 Brit Power-Shok 180 Grn Speer Hot-COR SP ammo- 4 Original blued steel British stripper clips- 17 Original parkerized steel British stripper clips (various markings)- 20 Once fired PPU brass- 5 Once fired original surplus GB49 Mk7 brass Message for questions or more pictures

title: For Sale:  45 ACP - 1,000 rds, 230 gr. New FMJ, Brass Case
postcontent: New, 230 gr., FMJ, Brass Case. X-Treme Bullets features copper plating applied electrochemically to a precision swaged lead core. The base of the bullet is also fully coated in copper. X-Treme Bullets are proudly made out of the finest materials available in the United States in order to ensure performance delivered down range with each and every shot. The process starts with a lead billet that is extruded into wire. The lead wire is then swaged into a core. The cores are copper plated, then re-struck once more. Though not common in the industry, this restrike process produces a bullet that is more uniform, with a more precise diameter and a smoother finish for a better shooting and a better looking bullet. X-Treme Bullets Copper Plated projectiles are re-struck to ensure our diameters are precise and consistent from bullet to bullet and lot to lot.
